  "en_notes_asad": [
    {
      "note_no": "208",
      "note": "Although the majority of the commentators attribute to the term amah, occurring in this context, its usual connotation of \"slave-girl\", some of them are of the opinion that it stands here for \"God's bondwoman\". Thus, Zamakhshari explains the words amah mu'minah (lit., \"a believing bondwoman\") as denoting \"any believing woman, whether she be free or slave; and this applies to [the expression] 'believing bondman as well: for all human beings are God's bondmen and bondwoman\". My rendering of the above passage is based on this eminently plausible interpretation."
    }
  ],
  "en_snotes_yusuf": null,
  "en_snotes_asad": "Although the majority of the commentators attribute to the term amah, occurring in this context, its usual connotation of \"slave-girl\", some of them are of the opinion that it stands here for \"God's bondwoman\". Thus, Zamakhshari explains the words amah mu'minah (lit., \"a believing bondwoman\") as denoting \"any believing woman, whether she be free or slave; and this applies to [the expression] 'believing bondman as well: for all human beings are God's bondmen and bondwoman\". My rendering of the above passage is based on this eminently plausible interpretation.",
